endency in which touching and breathing, capacities that amid a viral outbreak can threaten life itself, challenge the boundaries of the body and selfhood. Criticizing notions of unlimited personal liberty and the killing forces of racism, sexism, and classism, this book suggests that the pandemic illuminates the potential of shared vulnerabilities as well as the injustice of pervasive inequalities.Exposing and opposing forms of injustice that deny the essential interrelationship of living creatures, Butler argues for a radical social equality and advocates modes of resistance that seek to establish new conditions of livability and a new sense of a shared world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLifexHistoryy21st century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh  aCOVID-19.  aMaurice Merleau-Ponty.  aMax Scheler.  aclimate change.  aethics.  afeminist theory.  aglobal inequality.  aintersubjectivity.  apandemic.  aphenomenology.  aprecarity.  apsychoanalysis.  asexism.  ashared world.  astructural racism.  athe body.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2022 Englishz978311099276208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2022z9783110992755oZDB-23-DPH0 cprintz978023120828440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/butl2082840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231557351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231557351/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Com